english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry Selection of Eight Masters
  author: Park Peng-nyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Between heaven and earth flows a single vital force. When humans receive this force and give it voice, it becomes language; and poetry is the very essence of language refined. Thus, by observing the poems and songs of men, we may discern the waxing and waning of heaven and earth's vital energies. I have held this conviction for many years.

    Hitherto, Bihaedang, together with other scholars, has gathered poems from eight masters—Li Bai, Du Fu, Wei Yingwu, Liu Zongyuan, Ouyang Xiu, Wang Anshi, Su Shi, and Huang Tingjian—compiling them into several volumes. Upon examining this collection, I am convinced that since the age of the Classics of Poetry and the Songs of Chu, only the Tang and Song dynasties have truly flourished. And among Tang and Song, these eight masters stand forth most brilliantly. Thus Bihaedang's diligence in this work is most fitting.

    Yet the vital force of heaven and earth more readily decays than endures. Literature and the way of the world rise and fall with it. Song falls short of Tang; Tang of Han and Wei; Han and Wei of the ancient Classics. As an aged man cannot return to youth, so too the descent of ages. Only the exceptional and heroic escape the mold, unswayed by the transformations of their times.

    By the twilight of Qi and Liang dynasties, the poetic way had nearly perished. Then came Tang's Li Bai and Du Fu to revive it; Wei Yingwu and Liu Zongyuan followed in harmony. In the Five Dynasties it declined again, until Song brought forth Ouyang Xiu and Wang Anshi to restore it; Su Shi and Huang Tingjian continued their legacy. Now, reading their verses and contemplating their persons across a thousand years hence, one's heart awakens to reverence. Glorious indeed!

    Yet the masters of poetry accord only Li Bai and Du Fu the highest rank, while opinions on Wei, Liu, and the rest remain divided. This too must be understood.

    Whoever studies this selection, if they would burnish and cleanse themselves of commonplace tastes, trace the streams flowing from Huang and Su, ascend to the platform of Li and Du, and enter at last into the hall of the ancient Classics—they shall not betray the purpose of this collection. So strive with resolve.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''eight masters'' referenced are Tang and Song dynasty poets selected for their influence and artistry: Li Bai and Du Fu (Tang), Wei Yingwu and Liu Zongyuan (Tang), Ouyang Xiu and Wang Anshi (Song), and Su Shi and Huang Tingjian (Song).'
    - The 'Classics of Poetry' (Feng) and 'Songs of Chu' (Sao) represent the pinnacle of ancient Chinese verse, before the literary flourishing of the Tang and Song dynasties.
